Q2

Calculate ROAS (Return on advertising spent) and round it to two decimals

kag$ROAS <- round((10*kag$Total_Conversion + 50*kag$Approved_Conversion)/kag$Spent,2)

Q6

The average amount of time customers will wait in line under the current restaurant scenario is 7 minutes (rounding to the nearest integer)

lambda <- 62 # customers per hour - arrival rate
mew1 <- 70 # customers per hour - service rate
Lq1 <- (lambda^2)/(mew1*(mew1-lambda))
Wq1 <- Lq1/lambda
Wq1*60
## [1] 6.642857

Q7

Plot the average wait time for a constant 14 customers/hour when the number of servers varies from 7 to 20 (service rate of 82 customers/hour)

lambda2 <- ((7:20*14)*0)+82 # customers per hour - arrival rate
Servers <- 7:20
mew3 <- 7:20*14 # customers per hour - service rate
Lq3 <- (lambda2^2)/(mew3*(mew3-lambda2))
Wq3 <- (Lq3/lambda2)*60
plot(x=Servers,y=Wq3,xlab = "Number of Servers",ylab="Average Wait Time (mins)")

Q8 a

Based on the plot above, the average customer wait time drops below 3 minutes with 8 servers.

Q8 b

Based on the plot above, the average customer wait time decreases with additional servers. The most drastic change occurs adding 1 server (from 7 to 8), which reduces the wait time by about a half. The most optimal staffing would be at 10 servers at the curves elbow. As the number of servers reaches infinity, the average wait time approaches zero.
